and we helped place all those people. The only year

23:24.450 --> 23:30.010
that I couldn't get them placed was, I believe, in 
about 1980 when enrollment had just gone out of

23:29.990 --> 23:33.050
proportion. And at the same time, the job market 
dropped completely. So we had a real problem then.

23:41.340 --> 23:44.240
But then Benson was after Calhoun. After Calhoun. 
Calhoun really wasn't deemed very long. Right.

23:47.460 --> 23:48.881
Now, he moves up to what? Oh. Was he assistant? He 
was, went up to vice-presidential,

23:51.120 --> 23:56.710
vice-president for engineering, I think. Right. 
When did you first meet Fred Benson? Well, I met him

24:01.500 --> 24:04.660
before he became dean. I knew him because we were 
both in a naval reserve unit together. And he

24:08.320 --> 24:11.780
wasn't very, and we actually were taking one of the 
math courses there together at one time. He was

24:14.080 --> 24:16.820
taking one course, a lower one than I was taking. 
Did he do his degree here? Yeah, he got, he got his BS

24:19.440 --> 24:21.260
at Calhoun. Oh. He got his B.S. at Kansas. And then 
he got a master's several years back at here. Okay.

24:27.760 --> 24:28.681
As I recall. And then he was taking some additional 
courses. Describe Fred Benson as a human being, as

24:31.700 --> 24:35.300
a personality. Well, we got along just fine. One of 
the things, when I got appointed, what he did was

24:38.640 --> 24:42.840
call me in one afternoon. He said, Charlie, I'd 
like for you to take over here as head of the

24:42.820 --> 24:47.350
department. Said, now, you don't have to tell me 
right now. You can wait until a little bit. A little

24:51.970 --> 24:54.110
later and tell me if you think it over. And so I did. 
And I wasn't really sure I wanted to. I really

24:58.640 --> 25:03.150
wanted to tell him, how about getting old Doc to 
take it one more year? I'd like to do the things I'm

25:03.210 --> 25:05.590
doing a little longer. But I decided to go ahead and 
take it because I thought that I could probably do

25:05.570 --> 25:11.750
more things that I wanted to do if I were head than I 
could if they got somebody from the outside and he

25:16.370 --> 25:18.530
started giving me all kinds of directions. When 
was that? What year? That was in 19... 1964. Right.

25:24.610 --> 25:25.631
What... At that point, you said things you wanted 
to do. What were your goals? Well, we had a... I'd

25:29.930 --> 25:38.630
gone to Exxon in 55 and gotten started modeling, 
doing distillation on computers and actually

25:38.610 --> 25:42.130
setting up programs to solve problems on them. And 
I worked with them, consulted with them, and I had

25:42.110 --> 25:45.630
graduate students. We'd try out new methods and we 
had an old 650 and that's what they had down at

25:45.610 --> 25:51.250
Exxon. And we had an old 650 and they put it up in the 
old EE building. Now this is an old key punch? Yeah,

25:57.230 --> 25:58.251
yeah. Punch card? It was up in the building. And my 
graduate students would go up there and use it at

26:00.230 --> 26:02.250
night. And it had a fire escape and so they'd go up to 
the fire escape and run that thing all night long.

26:07.230 --> 26:08.251
That's what we did. That's the way we got our time. 
And we had a lot of that going on. I'd written a book

26:11.520 --> 26:17.540
and a good many papers on it of methods that we had 
devised to solve these problems. So this was

26:18.520 --> 26:19.541
primarily... At this point, primarily... At this 
point, primarily petrochemically related.

26:23.520 --> 26:24.541
Yeah. Or you can do chemical either one. It's used 
in both fields, not just one. But back to Benson.

26:38.740 --> 26:39.761
Describe him. What did he like and not like? How did 
he operate? Well,

26:42.740 --> 26:49.370
I think although he would claim that he wanted 
everybody to say what they wanted to. He wanted to

26:50.350 --> 26:52.370
hear the right words. And he had around him people 
that he knew would always back him up. I remember I

26:57.350 --> 27:01.630
used to go in there to budget hearings. And he'd 
have Ed Fenner. Then he'd have Old Bain, Spencer.

27:08.280 --> 27:11.490
And he'd have two or three others like that. And 
he'd say something and they'd all chime in and

27:11.470 --> 27:16.490
agree. But he and I got along pretty well because I 
never did... I never did go in and ask him to solve my

27:19.470 --> 27:22.490
problems for me. I went ahead and solved the 
things. And the only time he and I got crosswise was

27:25.470 --> 27:33.160
he was pushing real hard for this Doctor of 
Engineering program. And he had all of us

27:35.070 --> 27:38.090
department heads in there one day. And what he was 
wanting us to do was agree not to weaken down the

27:38.070 --> 27:43.486
B.S. degree to where it would not be an accredited 
degree and have the Doctor of Engineering be the

27:44.070 --> 27:49.090
first accredited degree. And I stood up against 
him because I told him that we could not afford to

27:50.070 --> 27:56.380
have a large group of students coming out of here 
without an accredited degree. If we're going to

28:00.360 --> 28:02.116
give a B.S. degree, we'd better make it 
accredited. And he got so mad at me that he walked

28:04.840 --> 28:10.860
out and stayed gone for about 15 minutes. And then 
we finally decided we'd have it kind of optional.

28:17.160 --> 28:18.181
If they wanted... We'd always have the B.S. 
accredited. But if they wanted to go at an early

28:21.260 --> 28:25.280
stage somewhere over to the Doctor of 
Engineering, they could. And so we'd just leave it

28:26.260 --> 28:32.280
where whichever one won out would be the way we'd 
go. And I told him we were just not big enough to

28:32.260 --> 28:38.630
fight against the whole United States on one 
program like that. They'd run us out of business.

28:41.610 --> 28:43.630
So he and I... And then later he says, Charlie, you 
can do whatever you want to. He didn't.

28:50.610 --> 28:51.631
He just patted me down. And I said, Well, good for 
you. It was kind of bad that he wasn't here. He

28:56.610 --> 28:57.631
thought it was anity, or something. But I knew I was 
getting ready to die, and that I was going to get out

29:04.110 --> 29:06.150
and make a living myself. But I never really gave 
him any good results, and friends I met back in

29:06.130 --> 29:11.630
college, I don't remember some of them. Well, 
Chuck, he wasn't fit for engineering cars to date.

29:14.610 --> 29:15.631
That's what I think of it. Mitchell was a 
four-year-old swimmer. and you could make a good

29:16.610 --> 29:20.010
program out of that where you would actually do 
research on things that pertain to engineering

29:22.070 --> 29:24.390
per se more than you can on some of the directions 
they're going in because they get toward the

29:28.750 --> 29:32.360
science end of it, and then you're dealing with the 
physicists or the chemists and so on. So it was a

29:35.000 --> 29:36.581
good degree. It was just that I didn't think that we 
could swing it. What did happen to it? Well, I think

29:42.200 --> 29:45.360
they still give some of them, but there just wasn't 
the demand for it. It's just hard to sell. All

29:51.720 --> 29:54.220
right, so there was a key decision. That I had 
something to do with. I saved him there, really. In

29:59.440 --> 30:02.160
Benson's personality, did he laugh much? No, he 
was always just in the meetings. There was never

30:06.010 --> 30:07.191
much said. And he got to the point pretty quickly, 
didn't he? Oh, yeah, yeah. And it was well thought

30:13.100 --> 30:16.240
out. Anything he did was well thought out. He was 
good to work for. I didn't have a bit of trouble

30:20.490 --> 30:22.530
working for him. I mean, he knew that I wasn't back 
down anymore. I expressed my opinion. He didn't

30:30.670 --> 30:34.370
like it, but he respected it, and then he told me 
later, I think he really, it hurt him that he

30:37.410 --> 30:39.710
couldn't handle it better than he did. In your 
early years as department head, who were your key

30:43.230 --> 30:45.530
associates? As department heads elsewhere in 
engineering and anywhere else? Oh, well,

30:52.270 --> 30:53.990
actually, in those years, I knew all the 
department heads real well. But who were the ones

30:56.610 --> 30:59.190
you worked with most? Well, I knew Samang real 
well. He and I were well acquainted. Describe him.

31:04.850 --> 31:10.380
Well, he was very precise and very fair, and I had a 
lot of respect for him, and he did for me. Describe

31:18.280 --> 31:20.780
him physically.

